Wiki Text:
The company was incorporated in 1992 in North Dakota for the purpose of engaging in the property and casualty insurance business. It is a subsidiary of XL Specialty Insurance Company and an indirect subsidiary of XL Reinsurance America Inc. In 2013, the company re-domesticated from North Dakota to Delaware with regulatory approval. In September 2018, AXA S.A. became the ultimate parent of AXA XL Group and its affiliates through a merger with XL Group Ltd.

XL Reinsurance America Inc. owns 100% of XL Specialty, Greenwich Insurance Company, and Catlin Specialty Insurance Company. XL Specialty owns 100% of IHIC and Catlin Insurance Company, Inc. Greenwich Insurance Company owns 100% of XL Insurance America Inc., which in turn owns 100% of XL Select Insurance Company and XL Insurance Company of New York, Inc.

The company's capitalization includes 50,000 shares of common stock with a par value of $100. As of December 31, 2020, all 50,000 shares were issued and outstanding, totaling $5,000,000. All outstanding shares are owned by XL Specialty. The company reported gross paid-in and contributed surplus of $103,918,879.

The company received several capital contributions from its parent, XL Specialty, including $30,000,000 in December 2020, $15,000,000 in June 2020, $8,000,000 in March 2020 and December 2018, $5,000,000 in November 2017, and $1,000,000 in March 2016.

ACE Limited has completed its acquisition of Chubb, creating the world's largest publicly traded property and casualty insurance company. The transaction, totalling $29.5bn in cash and stock, includes the transfer of the Chubb name globally. The new Chubb brand will begin trading under the symbol “CB” on the New York Stock Exchange. Fitch Ratings has placed a number of the financial strength (IFS) ratings of ACE’s operating subsidiaries under review following the merger. The rating agency has stated that it will “…review how this transaction may enhance or adversely affect the individual standalone ratings of these ACE subsidiaries”, including ACE Seguros, life subsidiary BBA and life reinsurer, ACE INA Holding Inc. The new company will start operations from Friday, consolidating underwriting offices in London and Bermuda. The combination is expected to open new growth opportunities in the US market, but analysts are predicting cost savings could put thousands of jobs at risk worldwide.

Arch Capital Group, a company that specializes in reinsurance, insurance, and mortgage insurance, has been expanding its operations since its launch in 2001. In 2002, the company brought in $1.26 billion in net premiums written. It continued to grow and open offices in Toronto, Canada and London, England by 2005. In 2019, the company acquired the UK commercial lines business of the Ardonagh Group and launched its primary mortgage insurance operations in Australia. It also started underwriting property and casualty, motor, and other business lines through its EU arm in Ireland. 

ACE Limited has completed its acquisition of Chubb, creating the largest publicly traded property and casualty insurance company in the world. The acquisition was valued at $29.5 billion and included the transfer of the Chubb name globally. The new company will operate under the Chubb brand and will begin trading on the New York Stock Exchange. The combination is expected to create new growth opportunities in the US market, but there are concerns that cost savings from the merger could result in job cuts worldwide. Fitch Ratings has placed the financial strength ratings of ACE's subsidiaries under review following the merger, to assess how it may impact their individual ratings.

Tokio Marine Holdings agreed to acquire US insurer, HCC Insurance Holdings, for $7.5bn in cash. The deal will expand Tokio Marine's product offerings and capabilities, as well as providing it with an international footprint. It will also strengthen the non-life insurer’s position in the US, the world's biggest market. Nikkei added that the acquisition, if completed, would lift Tokio Marine up from 12th place to eighth or ninth among global insurers in terms of capital. As we highlighted last month, the ageing population of Japan is believed to be eroding the profitability of local insurers, including the four largest in Japan - Tokio Marine, Nippon Life Insurance, Meiji Yasuda Life Insurance, and Dai-ichi Life Insurance - and pushing them to seek growth opportunities overseas. Tokio Marine said the offer represents a 38% premium to HCC’s closing price on Tuesday and they are hoping to close the deal, which is subject to approval by HCC’s shareholders and regulators, in Q4 2015.

Based in Morristown, New Jersey, the United States Fire Insurance Company has been offering a wide range of insurance services since its establishment in 1824. These services include health, automobile, burglary, and fire insurance, along with underwriting services. A subsidiary of Crum & Forster Holding, the company's assets are guided and maintained by its board of directors.

Entity Name: Travelers Cas & Surety Co Of Amer
Wiki Text: Based in Hartford, Connecticut, Travelers Casualty and Surety Company was founded in 1883. The company, a subsidiary of Travelers Insurance, provides various insurance services including property, aircraft, automobile, credit, fire, and casualty insurance.

AIG Specialty Insurance Company, formerly known as Alaska Insurance Company and Chartis Specialty Insurance Company, is a subsidiary of American International Group (AIG). It was incorporated in Alaska in 1973, changed its name to American International Surplus Lines Insurance Company in 1989, and re-domesticated to Illinois in 2007. The company finally adopted its current name in 2013. AIG Specialty operates as a non-admitted insurer in 49 states and the District of Columbia.

AIG Specialty participates in an intercompany pooling agreement with 11 other affiliates, including National Union Fire Insurance Company, American Home Insurance Company, and Lexington Insurance Company. Under this agreement, AIG Specialty cedes 100% of its premiums to National Union but does not receive a share of the pool's combined results. The financial strength of AIG Specialty is heavily dependent on the underwriting performance of its pool members, the credit risk of AIG, and its own investment portfolio.

Sompo Holdings has completed its acquisition of Endurance Specialty Holdings for $6.3bn. The deal, which was announced in October 2016, has received approval from regulatory authorities and has met other closing conditions. As a result of the acquisition, Endurance will become part of Sompo Holdings, with a new entity called Sompo International being created in Bermuda. Sompo International will serve as a global commercial insurance and reinsurance platform. It will also incorporate Sompo Holdings' existing international commercial insurance and reinsurance businesses. The integration aims to provide customers with a wide range of insurance products across global markets. All Endurance business, with the exception of ARMtech, will be conducted under the Sompo International brand. Sompo America and SJNK Europe will also be rebranded Sompo International, although Sompo Canopius will remain a separate brand working closely with Sompo International. The new entity will have its own board, led by John Charman as chairman and CEO. The completion of the acquisition will enhance Sompo's presence in international markets and provide opportunities for global diversification.

Nationwide has announced the completion of the rebranding of Scottsdale Insurance Company to Nationwide. The company will continue to offer excess & surplus and specialty solutions as the E&S/Specialty business unit. Nationwide made the decision in September 2014 to convert all of its operations to leverage its strongest brand asset, "Nationwide is on your side." The rebranding will combine the strength of Nationwide's brand with the expertise of its E&S/Specialty team to fuel growth and strengthen the company's position in the industry. Agents and brokers in the excess & surplus and specialty marketplace will benefit from the stability of a Fortune 100 company with superior credit ratings, as well as the agility and responsiveness of a niche insurance carrier. Nationwide's E&S/Specialty team will continue to underwrite products with Scottsdale Insurance and affiliated companies and will remain in Scottsdale, Arizona. The Scottsdale campus is home to around 1,500 associates who support various Nationwide business lines. Nationwide is committed to maintaining its values and providing specialized solutions for its agency partners.
N/A

Beazley is a global specialist insurance company that provides its services to clients worldwide. Part of the Lloyd's market ecosystem, Beazley has a significant presence through Lloyd's broker network. This network and the market's trading licenses grant Beazley ample access to insurance and reinsurance businesses globally.

Accredited Holding Corporation has signed a merger agreement with a subsidiary of Randall & Quilter America Holdings. Accredited is the holding company for Accredited Surety and Casualty Company, a specialist insurer based in Florida. Accredited Surety holds active licenses in 49 US states and the District of Columbia, is listed by the Treasury, and has received an A- rating from A.M. Best. The company is a leading provider of bail bond insurance in the US and has a strong network of high-quality agents. Following the merger, Accredited will continue to be led by its existing management team, including Deborah Snow as President and CEO, Sharon Jallad as COO, Marney Emel as CFO, and AJ Campofiore as Chief Business Development Officer. The merger will enable Accredited to benefit from the resources and support of Randall & Quilter, a global provider of insurance and reinsurance services. The merger agreement marks an important milestone for Accredited and positions the company for further growth and success in its specialist insurance markets.
Note: Parent company acquired in 2014, but founded in 2020

Wiki Text: Ascot Specialty Insurance Company, originally known as Frontier Insurance Company, was incorporated in Rhode Island in 1974. It went through several name changes, becoming Coventry Insurance Company in 1986 and then going dormant in 1989. In 2017, it was acquired by Greyhawk Insurance Company and renamed Greyhawk Specialty Insurance Company. Later in 2018, Greyhawk Insurance Company and Greyhawk Specialty Insurance Company were both acquired by Ascot US Holding Corporation, a subsidiary of Ascot Group, Ltd, which is fully owned by the Canada Pension Plan Investment Board. The company was revitalized and recapitalized in 2018 to expand its business writing in the fields of Environmental Liability, Professional Lines, Mergers and Acquisition, and Property. This expansion is made possible through its Lloyds syndicate 1414 and its programs and program business. Ascot Specialty obtained eligibility in New York in May 2019 and is currently licensed in Rhode Island. It is eligible to write surplus lines insurance in forty-nine states and the District of Columbia.

North American Capacity Insurance Company (North American Capacity) was originally founded as American Capacity Insurance Company in Illinois in March 1986. It became a subsidiary of RLI Corporation and then was acquired by Swiss Re Limited in January 1991. After the acquisition, the company changed its domicile to New Hampshire and adopted its current name in May 1991. Under Swiss Re, North American Capacity is now a wholly owned subsidiary of Westport Insurance Corporation. The company has been authorized to provide surplus lines insurance in New York since August 10, 1992. As of December 31, 2021, North American Capacity is a domestic surplus lines insurer in New Hampshire and holds a license as an admitted insurer in Illinois. It operates on a non-admitted basis in forty-eight states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and the U.S. Virgin Islands.

BCS Insurance Company, also known as BCS Insurance, is an Illinois-based insurer located in Oakbrook Terrace. Founded in 1950, this company offers a range of insurance products such as automobile, disability, liability, and marine insurance. BCS Insurance Company operates as a subsidiary of the BCS Financial Corporation and is guided by a board of trustees.

Landmark American Insurance Company (Landmark American) was originally incorporated in the State of Oklahoma in February 1976. After a series of acquisitions, it came under the ownership of Guaranty National Corporation in 1980 and later Royal & SunAlliance USA, Inc. in November 1999. Since September 2003, Alleghany Corporation has held financial control over the company. In October 2016, Landmark American re-domesticated to New Hampshire.Beginning on September 4, 1991, Landmark American became eligible to write surplus lines business in New York. As of December 31, 2021, it operates as a New Hampshire-based domestic surplus lines insurer. The company conducts non-admitted operations in forty-nine states, including the District of Columbia, American Samoa, Puerto Rico, and the U.S. Virgin Islands.

Continental Casualty Company provides property and casualty insurance underwriting services to a wide variety of businesses and professionals. The company was established in 1897 with the initial purpose of offering accident and disability insurance for employees in the railroad industry.As of the close of 2014, CCC, along with its subsidiaries, reported a statutory surplus of $11.2 billion.

Associated Industries Insurance Company, originally known as Southeastern Surety Company, was formed in Florida in October 1953. Over the years, it underwent several name changes and operational transitions. It became Southeast Title and Insurance Company in 1959 and operated as Associated Industries of Florida Property & Casualty Trust, a domestic commercial self-insurance fund, from 1987 to June 1996. The company was acquired by Associated Industries Insurance Services, Inc. in December 1994 and officially adopted its current name in January 1996. Since September 2007, AmTrust Financial Services, Inc. has held financial control of the company. As of June 12, 2012, Associated Industries became authorized to provide surplus lines insurance in New York. Currently, the company holds licenses in Florida and operates as a non-admitted insurer in forty-nine states and the District of Columbia.

AXIS Surplus Insurance Company (AXIS Surplus) was originally established as Sheffield Insurance Company in November 1986 in Alabama. It later changed its name to Sheffield Insurance Corporation in 1987. In June 1992, the company was acquired by Combined Specialty Group, Inc. and then re-domesticated to Illinois in January 2000. AXIS Capital Holdings Limited acquired the company in February 2003 and it subsequently adopted its current name. The company became eligible to write surplus lines business in New York on October 31, 2003. As of December 31, 2021, AXIS Surplus is an approved surplus lines insurer in fifty states, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico, operating as an Illinois domestic surplus lines company.

Columbia Casualty Company, initially established as Columbia Fire Insurance Company in Nebraska in February 1900, ceased operations in 1912. In 1919, the corporate charter was transferred to the National Fire Insurance Company of Hartford. Then, in 1973, the charter was sold to Continental Casualty Company, the parent company of National Insurance Company of Hartford. To reactivate the charter and change the company's domicile, Columbia Casualty Company of Illinois was incorporated in March 1974. It subsequently dropped the "Illinois" from its title and became Columbia Casualty Company. Continental Casualty Company, in turn, is owned by CNA Financial Corporation, with 90% ownership by Loews Corporation. Columbia Casualty has been authorized to write surplus lines business in New York since 1989. As of December 31, 2021, Columbia Casualty is an Illinois-based surplus lines insurer operating on a non-admitted basis in forty-nine states, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico.

German reinsurance company Munich Re has agreed to acquire specialty insurer HSB Group from American International Group (AIG) for $742m. The acquisition is part of Munich Re's strategy to expand its presence in the US insurance market. HSB Group, headquartered in Connecticut, is a subsidiary of AIG and is known for providing machinery and equipment breakdown insurance, inspection, certification, and engineering consulting services. In 2007, HSB posted an after-tax profit of $158m and had a gross written premium income of $904m. Munich Re will fund the purchase entirely from existing resources and the transaction is expected to be completed by the end of Q1 2009, subject to regulatory approval. After the acquisition, HSB will be under the direct operating control of Munich Re America. Munich Re believes that the acquisition of HSB will help reduce the volatility of traditional reinsurance business and strengthen its position in high return specialised niche segments

Palomar Excess & Surplus Insurance Company (PESIC) was established as an Arizona-based surplus lines insurer in the second quarter of 2020. It obtained regulatory approval during the same period and began operations with an initial surplus of approximately $102.4M. PESIC holds authorization to underwrite all property and casualty insurance business on a non-admitted basis. PESIC operates as a direct wholly owned subsidiary of Palomar Insurance Holding, Inc. (PIH), a Delaware corporation. PIH, in turn, is wholly owned by Palomar Holdings Inc (PHI), and also owns Palomar Specialty Insurance Company (PSIC) and Palomar Insurance Agency, Inc., operating as Prospect General Insurance Agency, Inc. (PGIA). PSIC, domiciled in Oregon, is the primary operating subsidiary and is licensed as an admitted insurer in 30 states. PGIA is a managing general agency responsible for underwriting specialty insurance products for PSIC, PESIC, and third-party insurance companies.

Homeland Insurance Company of New York, headquartered in Canton, Massachusetts, was founded in 1988 as an insurance provider, specializing in property and casualty coverage. It functions as a subsidiary of OneBeacon Insurance Group.

The business that is now known as Allied World Specialty Insurance Company has gone through a series of name changes and acquisitions since its inception. It was first incorporated in North Carolina on January 14, 1972, as Peninsula Property and Casualty Company (PPCC). It eventually became known as Darwin National Assurance Company (DNA). On October 20, 2008, the company, then named DPUI, was purchased by Allied World Insurance Company (AWIC) from a company called AIH. After this acquisition, it was rebranded as AW Underwriters, Inc. (AWUI). The company is a fully-owned subsidiary of AWUI, and completely owns two Arkansas-based insurance companies: Allied World Surplus Lines Insurance Company (AWSLIC), previously known as both Darwin Select Insurance Company and Vantapro Specialty Insurance Company. The company adopted its current name, Allied World Specialty Insurance Company, on October 28, 2014. It's parent company, Allied World Assurance Company is a Fairfax subsidiary.

Liberty Surplus Insurance Corporation (Liberty Surplus) was established in June 1997 in New Hampshire as a subsidiary of Liberty Mutual Holdings Company, Inc. (LMHC). Financial and operational control of the company is maintained by LMHC. Since August 28, 1998, Liberty Surplus has been authorized to provide surplus lines insurance in New York. As of December 31, 2021, Liberty Surplus is licensed in New Hampshire and operates on a non-admitted basis in 49 states, the District of Columbia, Guam, Puerto Rico, and the U.S. Virgin Islands.

Entity Name: Allied World Assur Co US Inc
Wiki Text: Allied World Assurance Company Holdings, Ltd. is a global provider of insurance and reinsurance products. In 2017, Allied World was acquired by Canadian financial holdings company, Fairfax Financial Holdings Limited. It now operates around the world as a Fairfax subsidiary.

Established in 1979, AXIS Insurance Company provides a diverse range of insurance services, including aircraft, automobile, property and casualty, professional lines, terrorism, marine, energy, aviation, accident, health, and life insurance to its customers. Based in Alpharetta, Georgia, the company is a subsidiary of AXIS Capital Holdings. The board of directors oversees the management of the company's assets.

Illinois Union Insurance Company, formerly known as GATX Insurance Company, is a subsidiary of ACE American Insurance Company and operates under the Chubb group. It is based in Illinois and has been eligible to write surplus lines business in New York since 1989. As of December 2021, Illinois Union is a domestic surplus lines insurer in Illinois and operates on a non-admitted basis in 49 states and the District of Columbia.

Illinois Union participates in the 25-member intercompany Chubb Pool where it cedes business to Federal Insurance Company. Reinsurance for the pool is complex and flows through various intercompany and non-affiliate layers managed by Chubb. Therefore, the financial strength of Illinois Union depends heavily on the credit risk of Chubb and the investment risk of its own portfolio managed by Chubb.

Chubb is a globally recognized insurance holding company that was founded in 1882 and has operations in 54 countries and territories. In 2016, ACE Ltd, which was founded in Bermuda in 1985 and later domiciled in Switzerland, acquired the Chubb Group and merged the two entities. The rebranded group, Chubb, is one of the largest publicly traded insurance holding companies in the world. Chubb provides commercial and personal property and casualty insurance, personal accident and supplemental health insurance, reinsurance, and life insurance to a diverse range of clients.

AM Best rates both Chubb and its insurance subsidiaries, including Illinois Union Insurance Company. Chubb has consistently received high ratings from AM Best and S&P, with an 'A++'/'AA' rating and a financial size of XV ($2 billion and above) for the years 2018 through 2021.

Overall, Illinois Union Insurance Company operates as part of the strong and globally recognized Chubb group, benefiting from its financial strength and reputation in the insurance industry.

In 2020, Westfield Specialty Insurance Company (WSIC) was established as a surplus lines insurer based in Ohio. It began operating in the first quarter of 2021 with an initial capital base of $50 million. As a wholly owned subsidiary of Ohio Farmers Insurance Company Inc. (OFIC), WSIC operates as a stock insurance company. WSIC conducts business as a nonadmitted insurer in all U.S. states and the District of Columbia, with the exception of Iowa.

In September 2008, Arch Specialty Insurance Company (Arch Specialty) was established as a New York domiciled insurer. Financial and operational control of the company rests with its ultimate parent, Arch Capital Group Ltd. (Arch Capital), a Bermuda-based public company. Arch Specialty is authorized to provide surplus lines insurance in New York since February 27, 2009. As of December 31, 2021, Arch Specialty maintains its license as an excess and surplus lines insurer in New York, while operating as a non-admitted insurer in all other U.S. states and the District of Columbia. Arch Specialty actively participates in various treaties and facultative reinsurance programs to manage its risk exposures.

Berkley Assurance Company, originally known as Florida International Indemnity Company, was established in Florida in May 1980. It went through various name changes - Queensway International Indemnity Company (1997-2004) and North Pointe Casualty Insurance Company (2004-2010). During the latter period, it functioned as a subsidiary of North Pointe Holdings Corporation. It was acquired by W. R. Berkley Corporation (Berkley), and assumed its current name, on January 1, 2011. The company's base was moved to Iowa as of March 2011. Berkley Assurance has been sanctioned to undertake surplus lines business in New York since September 19, 2011. As at the end of 2021, it is licensed in Iowa and operates without admission in 49 states and the District of Columbia.

Aspen Specialty Insurance Company, also known as Aspen Specialty, was originally incorporated in North Dakota in September 1996. Initially, it was called Dakota Specialty Insurance Company and operated as a subsidiary of The Insurance Corporation of New York. In September 2003, Aspen Insurance Holdings Limited (Aspen Holdings) acquired the company which consequently resulted in the adoption of its current name. Since April 13, 2004, the company has had the authorization to conduct surplus lines business in New York. As of the end of 2021, Aspen Specialty operates as a domestic surplus lines insurer established in North Dakota. It operates on a non-admitted basis across 49 states and the District of Columbia.
Founded By: The Insurance Corporation of New York

Wiki Text: Allied World Surplus Lines Insurance Company, known as AW Surplus Lines, was originally incorporated in Delaware in December 1990 under the name Ulico Indemnity Insurance Company, as a subsidiary of the Ulico Casualty Company. By 1992, it had shifted its domestic base to Arkansas. The company was later bought by Darwin National Assurance Company in May 2005, adopting the name Darwin Select Insurance Company. In October 2008, the company was acquired by Allied World Assurance Company Holdings, AG or AW Holdings. AW Surplus Lines adopted its current identity in June 2014. Fairfax Financial Holdings, Ltd bought AW Holding in July 2017. AW Surplus Lines got the clearance to transact surplus lines business in New York in February 2008. As of December 31, 2021, AW Surplus Lines, based in Arkansas, operates as a non-admitted insurer in forty-nine states and the District of Columbia.

Zurich American Insurance Company was established under New York state law on June 3, 1998, and kicked off its operations on December 31, 1998. It was founded to serve as the domestication medium under Article 72 of the New York Insurance Law for the U.S. branch of Zurich Insurance Company. On December 31, 1998, all assets and liabilities of the branch were transferred to the Company, consequently ending the branch's existence. Zurich American is the flagship company in the Zurich American Insurance Group. It is based in New York but operates its headquarters in Schaumburg, Illinois. ZAIG, through its standalone legal entities, holds licenses in all 50 states, the District of Columbia, and several U.S. territories. It offers a variety of commercial insurance products and risk management services to both domestic and international companies. ZAIG manages its property and casualty insurance companies as one entity, thereby ruling out any operational or strategy-based distinction among the legal entities.

ACE Limited has announced the leadership team that will be appointed for its North America excess and surplus (E&S) lines wholesale business upon the completion of its acquisition of Chubb. The business will be named Westchester, a Chubb company, and will include wholesale business currently written in ACE Westchester, ACE Commercial Risk Services, Chubb Custom Market, Chubb Specialty Insurance, and Chubb Commercial Insurance. The acquisition is expected to close in the first quarter of 2016.

Bruce Kessler will serve as Senior Vice President of the new Chubb Group and Division President of Westchester, responsible for integrating the E&S, small commercial, and programs businesses within ACE and Chubb. David Lupica will serve as Chief Operating and Distribution Management Officer, with responsibility for the small commercial group. Westchester will focus on the Property, Casualty, Professional Risk, Inland Marine, Environmental, and Product Recall lines of business for wholesale distribution partners.

The leadership team for Westchester will consist of Bob Meyer, Dean Andrighetto, Joseph Casey, Rob Owens, and Florian Beerli, who will lead various lines of business. In the small commercial group, David Charlton will lead the Micro Specialty business, and Franklin Sanders, Jr. will lead the Programs business.

The company aims to broaden its capabilities in the wholesale market, invest in new technologies, and build out its distribution. The leadership team is expected to generate strong results and achieve ambitious targets for growth and profitability. Westchester's commitment to the wholesale market is demonstrated by the addition of small business specialty and programs leadership, and it aims to position itself as the specialty insurer of choice for a wide range of challenging risks.

Entity Name: Travelers Prop Cas Co Of Amer
Twin City Fire Ins Co Co

Wiki Text: Princeton Excess & Surplus Lines Insurance Company, also known as Princeton E&S, was founded and incorporated in Delaware in June 1995. Initially, it was created as a subsidiary under the name of The Princeton Excess & Surplus Lines Insurance Corporation, which was a part of the American Re Corporation. The company renamed itself to the present name in December 1995 and came under the financial control of Munich Re in August 1996. The organisation was given the green light to write surplus lines business in New York starting October 7, 2003. As of the last day of 2021, Princeton E&S, now a domestic surplus lines insurer of Delaware, works on a non-admitted basis in 49 states other than Delaware, including the District of Columbia.

The Allied World National Assurance Company (AW National) was first incorporated in New Hampshire in September 1996, going by the name of Newmarket Underwriters Insurance Company, as a subsidiary of Swiss Reinsurance Company. It was later purchased by Allied World Assurance Company Holdings, AG in July 2002 and changed its name in August 2007. In 2017, the company was further acquired by Fairfax Financial Holdings Limited (Fairfax). AW National has been authorized to conduct surplus lines business in New York since June 1997. As of the end of 2021, the company is licensed in 44 states and the District of Columbia, while also operating on a non-admitted basis in California, Delaware, and New York.

Evanston Insurance Company, known simply as Evanston Insurance, was established in Illinois in August 1977. From the time of its creation until 2015, no official company history was recorded. By 2015, it was owned by Markel Corp. (Markel). During this period, a series of consolidating mergers were carried out by Markel, where Altera E&S Insurance Company, Essex Insurance Company, and Associated International Insurance Company were integrated into Evanston Insurance in December 2015, June 2016, and December 2016 respectively. The financial and operational control of Evanston Insurance remains under Markel Corporation. The company has been authorized to engage in surplus lines business in New York since at least ELANY’s inception in 1989. By the end of 2021, Evanston Insurance was operating as a domestic surplus lines writer in Illinois and on a non-admitted basis across 49 states, the District of Columbia, Guam, Puerto Rico, and the U.S. Virgin Islands.

Fairfax Financial Holdings has agreed to acquire all outstanding registered ordinary shares of Allied World Assurance Company Holdings for approximately $4.9bn. Under the cash and share offer, Allied World shareholders would receive $54 per share, comprising $10 in cash and $44 in Fairfax subordinate voting shares. This represents an 18% premium to the closing price per Allied World share on 16 December. Fairfax can also choose to increase the total cash consideration payable to Allied World shareholders by up to $30 per share, taking the total cash per share to $40 if desired. The offer was unanimously supported by Allied World’s board. The merger will create a global leader in property and casualty insurance, reinsurance and investments, according to the company. It is subject to customary closing conditions, including approval by Allied World shareholders and regulatory approvals. Commenting on the merger, Prem Watsa, chairman and CEO of Fairfax, said: “Allied World is a high-quality company with an excellent long-term track record and an outstanding management team”. The acquisition will strengthen Fairfax’s worldwide operations and further diversify its group risk portfolio, the company said.

Markel Corporation has completed its acquisition of State National Companies, a provider of property and casualty insurance services. State National operates two core businesses, program and lender services. The acquisition was announced on 26 July 2017. Markel's Co-Chief Executive Officer, Richard R. Whitt, said the acquisition was exciting for many reasons, including the addition of a premier fronting platform through which insurance products can be offered throughout the US, as well as a recognised provider of collateral protection insurance to credit unions and regional banks. He also praised the people at State National and said their talent and integrity aligned with Markel's values. State National's Chairman and Chief Executive Officer, Terry Ledbetter, said the acquisition would enable the firm to offer clients unique, high-quality solutions with the support of Markel. State National will operate as an independent division of Markel. Markel Corporation is a diverse financial holding company that underwrites specialty insurance products.

Hudson Excess Insurance Company, was set up in May 2012 in Delaware as a subsidiary of the Odyssey Reinsurance Group (known as Odyssey Re). Fairfax Financial Holdings Limited, or Fairfax, ultimately has ownership of the company, retaining financial and operations control over Hudson Excess. The company secured eligibility to conduct surplus lines business in New York from April 29, 2013. As of December 31, 2021, Hudson Excess operates as a domestic surplus lines insurer in Delaware and runs on a non-admitted basis in forty-nine states, including the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and the U.S Virgin Islands.
